***Update: See comments below that clarify the analogous is also achievable with the _traditional_-for-loop.**

    final List&lt;Integer&gt; list = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();
    for(int i = 0; i &lt; 10; ++i){
        list.add(i);
    }
        
    int i = 1;
    while(i &lt; list.size()){
        if(list.get(i) % 2 == 0){
            list.remove(i++);

        } else {
            i += 2;
        }
    }

*No ConcurrentModificationException from that code.*

There we see looping not start at the beginning, and not stop at *every* element (which I believe `Iterator` itself can&#39;t do).

